From 0000000000000000000000000000000000000000 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Benjamin Perseghetti <bperseghetti@rudislabs.com>
Date: Wed, 8 Jan 2025 00:00:00 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] qemu-native: fix fchmodat2 libc syscall emulation

fchmodat2 was the only chmod-family syscall still on a raw safe_syscall
wrapper; chmod/fchmod/fchmodat already go through host libc. Under
QEMU_LIBCSYSCALL=1 the raw path bypasses pseudo's LD_PRELOAD wrappers, so
a chmod done via fchmodat2 is invisible to pseudo. glibc >=2.39 routes
fchmodat(...,AT_SYMLINK_NOFOLLOW) through fchmodat2, which shadow's
useradd/groupadd use when rewriting passwd/group/shadow/gshadow during
do_rootfs. The lost chmod leaves those files at shadow's 0600 creation
default (instead of 0644/0640), making /etc/passwd unreadable to non-root
on the target ("I have no name!"). qemu 10.0.6 had no fchmodat2 handler so
glibc fell back to libc fchmodat; qemu 10.2.x added a raw handler and broke
the fallback.

Route fchmodat2 through libc fchmodat when do_libcsyscall is enabled so
pseudo sees the mode change. Flag numerics are arch-independent, so no
target translation is needed.

Upstream-Status: Inappropriate [embedded specific]

Signed-off-by: Benjamin Perseghetti <bperseghetti@rudislabs.com>
---
 linux-user/syscall.c | 9 ++++++++-
 1 file changed, 8 insertions(+), 1 deletion(-)

diff --git a/linux-user/syscall.c b/linux-user/syscall.c
index 3daed0a..bbbbbbb 100644
--- a/linux-user/syscall.c
+++ b/linux-user/syscall.c
@@ -868,9 +868,15 @@ safe_syscall6(ssize_t, copy_file_range, int, infd, loff_t *, pinoff,
               int, outfd, loff_t *, poutoff, size_t, length,
               unsigned int, flags)
 #endif
 #if defined(TARGET_NR_fchmodat2) && defined(__NR_fchmodat2)
-safe_syscall4(int, fchmodat2, int, dfd, const char *, filename,
-              unsigned short, mode, unsigned int, flags)
+static int safe_fchmodat2(int dfd, const char *filename,
+                          unsigned short mode, unsigned int flags)
+{
+    if (do_libcsyscall) {
+        return fchmodat(dfd, filename, mode, flags);
+    }
+    return safe_syscall(__NR_fchmodat2, dfd, filename, mode, flags);
+}
 #endif
 
 /* We do ioctl like this rather than via safe_syscall3 to preserve the
-- 
